events__description: In late February 2018, heavy rains gave rise to damaging floods along the Ohio and Mississippi rivers.
During the middle of February, temperatures averaged above normal over a wide area of Central Asia, including eastern Kazakhstan, northern Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan, and much of Afghanistan.
Heavy rains and temperature swings triggered a long ice jam in Connecticut.
Every January through March, vast numbers of small fires spring up across the countryside in Southeast Asia. Those months usually bring cool, dry weather—perfect conditions for burning.

events__title: Cold Snap in the Northeast U.S.
events__description: As 2017 drew toward a close, Arctic air spilled into the eastern United States and Canada for several days.
A slow-moving weather system in the Mediterranean brought torrential rain and flash floods to Greece.
A combination of fires, urban pollution, and bad weather caused a remarkable build-up of haze over northern India and Pakistan.
Many farmers in India set fire to their fields to clear them before planting, a practice known as stubble burning.

The floating part of Antarctica’s Pine Island Glacier released a new, 185-square-kilometer iceberg. By late October 2017, the berg had fractured into pieces that are no longer large enough to be named and tracked.
The storm became the Atlantic Ocean basin’s first hurricane of 2017.
Fire is uncommon in Greenland, yet smoke plumes rose south of Disko Bay in August 2017.
Since July 2017,  a large bloom of phytoplankton has been coloring western Lake Erie.

Wildfires spread across the Adriatic coast of Montenegro after weeks of high temperatures in July. The Lustica peninsula has been the worst affected, where tourists and residents were forced to evacuate.
Warming summer waters and ample sunlight make conditions right for phytoplankton to reproduce in abundance.
Extreme heat in the U.S. Southwest is breaking meteorological records, canceling flights, and making life miserable for millions of people.
Several tributaries of the Mississippi River face record or near-record water levels.
The cyclone was one of the earliest Atlantic cyclones observed in the satellite record.
It is the first named cyclone of 2017 in the northern hemisphere.
Several weeks of intense rain have triggered severe floods and mudslides in Peru, Colombia and Ecuador.
A heat wave coupled with strong winds has fueled forest fires in central Chile in January 2017.

events__title: Mount Frankland National Park Fire, Western Australia

events__description: A bushfire in the Nuytsland Nature Reserve.
In August 2016, heavy monsoon rains pushed the Ganges and other rivers in eastern and central India above their banks.
On August 12, 2016, heavy rainfall started in Louisiana, sending area rivers toward historic crests and causing at least three fatalities and thousands of evacuated people.
High temperatures combined with drought have provided the perfect conditions for the outbreak of fires in northern Portugal.

The heaviest snow in two decades blanketed Lesotho in late July 2016. The storm prompted the airlifts of at least eight tourists, and caused the deaths of several shepherds in the Joe Gqabi District Municipality, according to news reports.

Lightning triggered dozens of forest fires in Siberia in late June, and may have burned 3000 hectares. The fires are located in remote areas, and reportedly do not pose a threat to inhabited areas at this time, but a state of emergency has been declared in Kezhemskogo, Boguchansky, Evenki and Motyginsky districts.

Storms in eight provinces in southern China - among them Hubei, Sichuan, Guizhou, Jiangxi, Yunnan, Zhejiang and Anhui - have caused severe floods and displaced over 200,000 people after days of heavy rain.
In May-June 2016, satellites captured images of a bloom in the North Sea.

Intense rainfall capped off the wettest month in Texas history, with a state average of 7.54 inches. The previous record was 6.66 inches in 2004. According to news sources, Texas was doused with more than 35 trillion gallons of rain in the month of May.
Mount Sinabung in Indonesia erupted on 21 May at 09:48 UTC (04:48 local time) and killed seven people in the nearby village of Gembar. The volcano is still erupting, pouring ash 3 km into the sky.
A destructive wildfire burned through Canada’s Northern Alberta region, razing neighborhoods in Fort McMurray and displacing tens of thousands of residents.

events__title: Mt. Sourabaya Volcano, Bristol Island, South Sandwich Islands
events__description: A volcano in the far South Atlantic appears to be erupting for the first time in 60 years.
Nearly two feet of rain has resulted in extensive flooding in Houston, Texas.

events__title: Lake Kivu Whiting Event, Rwanda/DR Congo
events__description: The lake in central Africa is in the middle of a whiting event caused by calcium carbonate precipitation.
A crack across the Nansen Ice Shelf in Antarctica has broken, shedding two icebergs—one large enough to earn the name C33.
In Nepal, the dry month of April always brings an increase in fire activity.
Smoke and charred forests are the result of fires burning in Thailand’s Huai Kha Khaeng Wildlife Sanctuary.
Smoke from the blaze streamed into neighborhoods in India’s most populous city.
Jeju Island and other areas of the southwest mainland received extensive snowfall in January.
Fires have damaged prized forests in northwestern Tasmania.
San Miguel (also known as Chaparrastique) is one of the most active volcanoes in El Salvador.
Hurricane Pali became the earliest hurricane on record in the Central Pacific when it achieved hurricane status 19 days earlier than the previous record holder, Hurricane Ekeka of 1992.

After battles in Libya on January 4–6, 2016, several fires were observed at oil production and storage facilities near Sidra, on the coast between Sirte and Benghazi. Smoke plumes from several oil tanks and facilities spread a pall of black smoke across the nation’s Mediterranean coast.
In December and January, heavy summer rains swamped this part of South America causing the Uruguay, Paraguay and Parana rivers to swell beyond flood stage.
Three days of heavy rain have caused widespread flooding in the United States, stretching from Illinois down to Mississippi.
Authorities in Beijing have issued a first-ever “red” air pollution alert.
After a two-year respite, Sicily’s massive Etna volcano is showing signs of life.
For the first time in more than a century, Nicaragua’s Momotombo Volcano awoke with an explosive eruption.
Mongolia is experiencing very low temperatures and heavy snowfall since early November 2015, locally named Dzud.
Bush fires have damaged power lines, burned 133,000 hectares, and destroyed two homes.
After forming in the Arabian Sea, Cyclone Chapala headed for the Arabian Peninsula.
Heavy rains in late October caused flooding in and around Baghdad, as surface drainage is minimal.

In late October 2015, Mount Rinjani (3,726m) on the Indonesian island of Lombok began erupting. In the days that followed, ash from Rinjani blanketed towns and farmland across three Indonesian islands and shut down air traffic to a number of airports. Rinjani last erupted in 2009–2010.
Heavy rainfall from a combination of tropical moisture and a non-tropical system resulted in heavy flooding in South Carolina.
During early September 2015, a cyclone-shaped wall of dust and a series of dust storms swept across the Middle East and Persian Gulf.
Smoke poured from seasonal fires in Indonesia in the fall of 2015.
Fires associated with a massive explosion in Tianjin, China, sent dark smoke drifting east and southeast.
A wall of dust rolled north from Sudan into southern Egypt.
The Reynolds Creek fire was reported in the afternoon of July 21 and has prompted evacuations within Glacier National Park.
A bloom of algae continues to grow in Lake Erie and surrounding waters.

events__title: Dust storm over Libya and Egypt

events__description: Dozens of uncontrolled fires are burning in northern Alberta and Saskatchewan.
The Tanana Area Fires include Spicer Creek, Bering Creek, Harper Bend, Moose Point, and Kokrine fires, all of natural causes.
The Lake Fire was reported just before 4:00 pm on June 17, 2015.
Tropical Storm Bill, the second named storm of the 2015 hurricane season, pushed ashore near Matagorda Island, Texas, on June 16, 2015.
The fast-moving Sockeye Fire has grown very quickly and is expected to continue to grow due to hot, dry weather.

events__title: Democratic Republic of the Congo Fires, June 2015
events__description: In June 2015, seasonal fires dotted central Africa.
Fires burned in the Northwest Territories, spreading smoke across the region.
After 33 years of inactivity, Wolf volcano in the Galapagos has reawakened.
Freshened surface water and abundant nutrients lead to an explosion of algae in the inland sea.

In the third week of May, it was warmer in Fairbanks, Alaska, than in Washington, D.C. The small town of Eagle, Alaska, was hotter on May 23 than it has been on any day in Houston or Dallas this year. In what has become a frequent occurrence in the past few years, temperature profiles in North America appeared to be upside down.
Calbuco volcano, located in the province of Llanquihue, state of Los Lagos, southern Chile, erupted on 22 Apr 2015.
One of the most active volcanoes on the Indonesian island of Java spewed fresh ash and gases in early July 2015.
